<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-882-036  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 882 036.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>DEC Professional  Sept 1989 v8 n9 p60(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Freeze, system manager! (Part 1: developing a case for computercrime) (includes related article on the Computer Security Act of1987)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sidrow, Christina L.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Systems managers need company crisis management guidelines andknowledge of relevant criminal law to effectively handle computercrime.andP;  Typical guidelines provide such goals as maintainingsecurity, aborting attempted break ins, and prosecuting securityviolations.andP;  The manager must understand the criteria forprosecution, how to build a case, and such legal issues as thedifferences between felony and misdemeanor crimes and betweencriminal and civil prosecution, the preparation of affidavits,private searches, preservation of evidence, working with thedistrict attorney, expert witnesses, restraining orders, falsearrest, sentencing and probation, and civil damages recovery.andO;Each of these topics is briefly discussed.andP;  Digital Equipment VAXcomputer SHOW USER, SHOW SYSTEM, and MONITOR commands and theAccounting utility are useful to watching user activity.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Statute:   Computer Security Act of 1987 (analysis).andO;Topic:     Computer CrimesPolicyManagement of EDPMethodsLegal IssuesMIS.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>